The IRS is about to see every dollar you made in crypto.

But probably not what you paid for it.

Here's what's happening:

If you traded on custodial exchanges (Coinbase, Kraken, Gemini, etc.) in 2025, they're sending Form 1099-DA to the IRS.

This form reports your GROSS PROCEEDS: the total dollar amount of every crypto sale you made.

Sold $100K worth of ETH? IRS sees $100K. Traded $50K of SOL for BTC? IRS sees $50K.

Now here's where it gets tricky:

Exchanges are NOT required to report your cost basis for 2025 transactions.

Cost basis = what you originally paid for the crypto.

When will your 1099-DA have cost basis?

ONLY if you bought AND sold/traded on the same exchange without ever moving the crypto (Most of us degens don't)

Example: You bought ETH on Coinbase and later sold it on Coinbase → cost basis included ✓

But if you:

Bought on Kraken, transferred to Coinbase, sold on Coinbase → cost basis BLANK
Bought on Coinbase, moved to your wallet, moved back, then sold → cost basis BLANK
Received crypto from another person or platform → cost basis BLANK
For most active crypto users who move funds between exchanges, wallets, or platforms, the cost basis field will be empty.

What happens next:

The IRS gets the same form you do.

When you file your taxes, YOU must report your cost basis on Form 8949.

If you don't... or if you can't prove it...

The IRS automated matching system flags your return and calculates tax as if you paid $0 for everything.

They treat your entire proceeds amount as pure profit.

$100K in sales becomes $100K in taxable gains.

That's the difference between owing $3,000 and owing $40,000.

The bottom line:

Mandatory cost basis reporting doesn't start until 2026.

For 2025, YOU need the receipts.

Trade confirmations. Transfer records. Purchase history. Wallet transfers. All of it.

No records = no proof = IRS assumes you made 100% profit.
